---

<PluginGuideLayout
  title="Make New Sounds in Ableton Live | Sonura Flow Setup Guide"
  description="Use Sonura Flow as a free-to-download VST3 plugin in Ableton Live. Start with free credits, then generate drums, loops, vocals, and one-shots inside your Ableton session."
  keywords="Ableton plugin, Ableton VST plugin, sample generator for Ableton, free Ableton plugin, Sonura Flow Ableton, sound generator Ableton"
  slug="ableton"
  headline="Make New Sounds in Ableton Live"
  subhead="Sonura Flow runs as a VST3 plugin in Ableton Live, so you can generate royalty-free drums, loops, vocals, and one-shots without leaving Arrangement or Session View."
  format="VST3 for Ableton Live"
  bestFor="Ableton producers, beat makers, loop writers"
  ctaText="Download the Ableton plugin"
  steps={[
    'Download Sonura Flow from the main plugin page and install the Mac or Windows version.',
    'Open Ableton Live and let it scan VST3 plugins. If needed, open Preferences, then Plug-Ins, and rescan.',
    'Create an audio track or MIDI track and load Sonura Flow from the VST3 plugin list.',
    'Sign in with your Sonura account, describe the sound you need, and generate up to four variations.',
    'Drag the generated audio into Arrangement View or Session View and keep writing.'
  ]}
  sections={[
    {
      title: 'Why Sonura Flow fits Ableton',
      body: 'Ableton is built around fast sketching, clips, resampling, and arrangement. Sonura Flow matches that workflow because generated audio can become a clip, a one-shot, a chopped sample, or the start of a new loop.',
      bullets: [
        'Create drum hits and drag them into Drum Rack.',
        'Generate melodic loops that match a project key or tempo idea.',
        'Make vocal chops, ad-libs, pads, and texture beds for resampling.',
        'Keep sound design inside the Live set instead of switching to a browser.'
      ]
    },
    {
      title: 'Best Ableton workflow',
      body: 'Use Sonura Flow early in a sketch when you need source material quickly. Generate several variations, keep the strongest one, then use Ableton tools like Simpler, Drum Rack, Warp, and audio effects to make the sound yours.'
    },
    {
      title: 'VST3 location notes',
      body: 'Ableton Live reads VST3 plugins from the standard system plugin locations on Mac and Windows. If Sonura Flow does not appear after installation, rescan plugins in Ableton Preferences and restart Live once.'
    }
  ]}
  faqs={[
    { question: 'Does Sonura Flow work in Ableton Live?', answer: 'Yes. Sonura Flow works in Ableton Live as a VST3 plugin on Mac and Windows.' },
    { question: 'Can I drag generated audio into Ableton clips?', answer: 'Yes. Generate a sound in Sonura Flow, then drag it into Arrangement View, Session View, Drum Rack, Simpler, or an audio track.' },
    { question: 'Is Sonura Flow free for Ableton users?', answer: 'Sonura Flow is free to download and free to start. New accounts include free credits, and more generations are available with paid Sonura plans.' },
    { question: 'Can I use the generated sounds commercially?', answer: 'Yes. Sounds generated with Sonura Flow are royalty-free and can be used in releases, client work, sync, and beats you sell.' }
  ]}
  relatedGuides={relatedGuides}
/>
